,Recommended,310890,14651490,"Posted: 25 February, 2015",all,Scapegoat,"While departing from the turn based strategy style gameplay of the original Breach & Clear Mighty Rabbit Studios has managed to not only improve upon their original title but to also breath new life into the tactical shooter genera. Ok so its not your typical tactical shooter in the sense that is not another FPS trying to  fill in the gap left by the original Rainbow Six that was released in 1998 but Breach & Clear: Deadline might be the first title I would consider as being a worth successor to the crown.Unlike most modern day tactical shooters employ the standard issue run and gun gameplay we could expect from any FPS on the market with the added benefit of being able to target enemies or issue orders to other members of your team. This doesn’t make a tactical shooter. Breach & Clear: Deadline attempts to recapture the tactical control feeling (which is a staple of the genera) that has been missing from other games. It does this by allowing the player to not only issue orders to units like the standard go there and shoot that options you would expect, in Breach & Clear: Deadline the player is able to  issue move commands, move units behind cover, highlight targets, assign arcs of fire, all while gameplay is frozen eliminating the cumbersome feeling of fiddling with controls on the fly. This doesn’t mean you can't just try and run-n-gun your way through the game because that’s also an option, it just wont get you very far.Along side the tactical shooter elements of the game there is also a good bit of a nostalgia due to the open world RPG style gameplay of the original Fallout series that will have you completing quests and looking for gear all while leveling up your squad and selecting different skills from the skill tree to upgrade each character and make your squad fit your play style.Now don't get me wrong Breach & Clear: Deadline isn’t perfect and it's still in development, but so far it has shown to be the model of what an Early Access title should be. First off I think pitting the player against zombies is a little dated at this point and the over all story could use some work. Luckily the developers are actively improving the game based on user comments and bug reports, patches come out to fix major issues fairly promptly, and their very responsive and appreciative of the online community."
