76561198014157371,Not Recommended,310890,21050221,"Posted: 8 February, 2016",all,aykeem,"Some of the features are implemented at a very basic level: looting implies running around the map, clicking on random crates and seeing what drops; character management implies selecting a specialization and putting points into a skill tree, but all classes play pretty much the same; upgrading gear means either using the game currency (scrap) to fill an upgrade bar or applying add-ons to guns, but is all in all kinda flavorless; the crafting economy basically boils down to ""kill zombies to get scrap, craft more of the same stuff"", very bare-bones.The UI is unintuitive and lacks feedback, takes a while getting used to. There are very few hints on how things work, what distinguishes the weapon types, what are the particularities of the zombie classes.And I could forget all of the above if the combat would be interesting, but it's not. The original Breach and Clear had a much more interesting combat system where setting up firing lines, crossfire, flanking maneuvers and getting into cover actually mattered. Here, it feels as if you just move your squad a bit, meet a bunch of enemies, stand still and kill them, then repeat. Someone compared this to XCOM in another review... this has nothing on XCOM in terms of tactical depth, as all enemies behave pretty much the same and squad positioning seems to be perfectly unimportant.I won't recommend this. It is a pity, though, it feels like this is a good base on which to build a good squad-based tactical strategy game, but there's just not enough depth."
