,Not Recommended,310890,17013315,"Posted: 12 July, 2015",all,CTi flauxhawk,"Deadline plays in two major modes: an 'Action' mode which bears similiarities to twin-stick shooters - and a 'Tactical' mode (a pause, issue orders, then go system) which allows you to precisely positions your troopers and issue them commands. These commands include using special abilities, directing their fire and utilizing equipment such as grenades and medkits. You have four troopers in your squad recruited from various classes, each replete with their own special abilities (suppression, explosives, etc.) Your characters gain experience and level up from completing missions and slaying enemies such as zombies and mercenaries. They can then expend skill points to unlock new abilities. Characters can even 'cross-class' if they save up the skill points, allowing you to develop more versatile characters. Aside from some of the active abilities the passives include 5% increased chance to crit, 5% increased damage with a particular weapon category or 5% increased health. They aren't spectacular on their own but if you cross-class the right classes you can find some abilities and upgrades that properly complement each other.Weapons, equipment and weapon modifications can be looted from crates and dead mercenaries. These weapons can also be modded provided they have the slots (up to 3). The weapon mods aren't terribly exciting though - they typically include items such as scopes, gas systems and triggers that either up the fire rate, improve accuracy or improve damage (while typically lowering accuracy). You can also spend scrap (in-game currency) to upgrade armor and weapons. However this just ups DPS or armor value by a set amount and the cost increases with each upgrade. Again, nothing too exciting there.The zombies come in a few flavors include shamblers, runners, acid spitters and some big hulking brutes. If you get swarmed your characters will easily be cut down. Luckily if you have a medic you can revive on the spot. Barring that your dead teammates will rejoin you when you visit a safehouse. Safehouses include workbenches for modding and upgrading weapons as well as storage for excess items.Mercenaries are distinguished by the weapons they wield - sniper rifles, assault rifles, shotguns, etc. They too can cut you down pretty quickly if you're exposed.There are 'dungeons' of a sort in-game. Certain areas have multiple floors that you can explore for loot and experience. Each level of the dungeon has an exit that takes you back to the starting point regardless of how deep you've made it. In addition they are interspersed with safehouse-like floors that refill health and allow you access to a workbench and locker. I'm not sure how 'deep' these dungeons go (the furthest I could stomach was about 8 floors in the Jupiter Building). Each floor or level isn't particularly different from the previous ones in layout so you do feel like you're exploring the same layout over and over after a few floors.Overall the game is enjoyable and fun, providing a mix of isometric-style shooting with some tactical direction. There is some character progression and development and while not as deep or exciting as I would like it works, especially with cross-classing. The missions and storyline have you backtracking quite a bit but the devs were kind enough to add in a fast-travel system so you aren't constantly walking back and forth.TL;DR: Military dudes shoot zambies in action or tactical mode. Level up, find equipment, customize characters.Post-release and patches edit: It seems that the developers have decided to throw in randomized zombie spawns during tactical gun battles with bandits, raiders, etc. While I could understand this as 'sound drawing the zombies to your location' the way it is currently handled is atrocious. I've had zombies spawn directly on top of my soldiers, directly behind with no warning. Previously zombies spawned outside of the combat zone and closed in on your location. Now they seem to spawn on top of you or behind you. This one change requires me to change my review to not recommended. This issue needs to be addressed for enjoyable, balanced gameplay.In addition human enemies with firearms can easily sit behind cover and almost never be hit while your own soldiers - behind comparable cover - easily get shot over and over again. There's really no point in trying to do anything other than tossing explosives in these situations as even the slightest attempt at suppression and flanking will see your men shredded within seconds."
